User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

October 30, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 67 responses, 31 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 46% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience, neurology, and related fields like neuropsychology and neuroimaging. Specifically, the areas of focus include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is a prominent area, encompassing various subfields such as attention, decision-making, learning, music cognition, language, predictive processing, and the cognitive neuroscience of aging.
  • Neurology & Neurodegenerative Diseases: Many respondents work on neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer’s and dementia, multiple sclerosis, stroke, and brain injury (including traumatic brain injury and sports-related injury).
  • Mental Health & Psychiatry: A significant number are involved in research related to mental disorders, including psychosis, mood disorders, ADHD, anorexia nervosa, and child/adolescent psychiatry. There’s also research focusing on psychotherapy and brain stimulation techniques.
  • Neuroimaging: This is a common methodology, with expertise in MRI (structural, functional, quantitative), fNIRS, EEG, and multimodal imaging. Some are focused on developing new contrasts and methods for MRI.
  • Aging & Development: Research on healthy aging, age-related cognitive decline, brain development, and related mental health issues is well represented.
  • Specialized Areas: This includes topics like sexual health, women’s health (menopause, menstrual cycle related symptoms), autoimmunity, pain, sensory processing (smell, taste, auditory), speech and language processing, and impulse control. There are also a few responses in more specialized areas like paleoclimatology using medical imaging, rehabilitation medicine, and environmental psychology.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, increased and improved access to MRI would significantly expand and improve research in several key areas:

1. Broadening Research Scope & Depth:

  • New Research Areas: Many researchers cited that increased MRI access would allow them to expand into new research areas they currently cannot explore, including:
    • Neural underpinnings of bilingualism
    • Early inflammatory changes in tissues (SLE patients)
    • Relationship between brain structure/function and pain
    • Neurotische imaging
    • Effects of interventions on brain anatomy/activity
    • Decoding of visual representation
    • Neuronal and neurochemical processes related to the menstrual cycle
    • Spinal cord research (thoracic and lumbar regions).
    • Geohazard diagnostic techniques in geological archives.
    • Interactions with artificial agents.
    • Cerebral Visual Impairments.
  • Deeper Investigations: Researchers would be able to conduct more in-depth investigations within their current fields, leading to a better understanding of:
    • Sexual dysfunctions and brain involvement.
    • Mechanisms of non-invasive brain stimulation.
    • Links between age-related brain changes and cognitive/motor performance.
    • Biomarkers for ADHD, especially in women across the lifespan.
    • Brain connectivity and microstructural changes in neurodegenerative diseases.
    • Epileptogenic lesions and epilepsy mechanisms.
    • Cognitive mechanisms.

2. Enhanced Research Quality & Power:

  • Larger Sample Sizes: Better access would allow for larger participant samples, increasing the statistical power and generalizability of research findings.
  • High-Quality Data: Access to high-performance fMRI and advanced sequences would improve the quality and precision of the data collected.
  • Longitudinal Studies: Stable, long-term access is crucial for longitudinal studies that track changes in the brain over time.
  • Reproducibility and Validation: The widespread use of MRI as a data collection method means that findings can be more easily reproduced and validated across different populations.

3. Collaboration and Multi-Center Studies:

  • Facilitating Collaboration: Improved access would make it easier to collaborate with researchers at other institutions, both within and outside of the country.
  • Multi-Center Studies: Participants emphasized the importance of MRI access for participating in larger, multi-center studies, which are essential for addressing complex research questions, particularly in rare or specific patient populations.

4. Clinical Translation & Impact:

  • Improved Diagnostics and Treatment: MRI research can lead to the identification of biomarkers for various conditions, informing more accurate diagnoses and individualized treatment approaches.
  • Clinically Relevant Information: MRI provides clinically relevant information for decision-making, tracking disease progression, and developing novel algorithms for clinical use.

5. Addressing Specific Needs & Challenges:

  • Flexible and Low-Cost Access: Researchers underscored the need for lower costs, and flexible scheduling.
  • Addressing Regional Disparities: Increased access is particularly important for researchers in regions with limited resources, such as northern Norway.
  • Support Infrastructure: Associated infrastructure for data storage, computation, and software are also vital.
  • Reducing Dependence on External Resources: Greater access and a suitable organizational model within the university/institution would reduce reliance on external data collection, which can be costly and time-consuming.

6. Career Advancement:

  • Securing Funding: Some researchers noted that a lack of MRI experience and publications has hindered their ability to secure grant funding. Better access to MRI would allow them to gain the necessary experience and generate pilot data, significantly increasing their chances of securing funding.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Several key themes emerged from the survey responses. Researchers highlighted the need for increased accessibility and prioritization of MRI resources for research purposes, potentially through the establishment of dedicated research scanners outside of hospital environments and a greater focus on research over clinical applications. A strong emphasis was placed on fostering collaboration and community among MRI researchers across Norway, potentially leveraging existing initiatives like MMIV and the expertise of individuals like Karsten Specht. Furthermore, respondents advocated for standardized capabilities across all sites and regularly scheduled, accessible research hours, balancing researcher needs with existing staff considerations. Finally, there was a call for advanced capabilities, specifically mentioning the need for at least one 7T scanner in Norway to facilitate studies of subcortical areas, and a vision for a distributed network of scanners enabling large-scale population mapping inspired by initiatives like the UK Biobank.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the overwhelming consensus from this survey emphatically underscores the critical need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners in Norway. The diverse range of researchers, spanning various disciplines and institutions, consistently highlighted the limitations imposed by the current scarcity of resources. From hindering participation in multi-center studies to delaying essential data collection and limiting the scope of innovative research, the lack of readily available MRI scanners poses a significant obstacle to advancing scientific understanding across numerous fields.

Furthermore, the respondents’ detailed justifications revealed the potential for transformative advancements with improved MRI access. These include more in-depth investigations into neurological disorders, enhanced understanding of cognitive processes, and the development of novel diagnostic and therapeutic approaches. The survey also revealed a need for increased support personnel and expertise to maximise use of such scanners.

This data provides compelling evidence for policymakers and funding bodies to prioritize investments in MRI infrastructure specifically designed to support research endeavors throughout Norway. By addressing this urgent need, Norway can unlock the full potential of its research community, foster groundbreaking discoveries, and solidify its position as a leader in cutting-edge biomedical research. The time for action is now.
